{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489519"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:19:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:19:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"680"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"680","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/680"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.52,0.23,0.2,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"680"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86589"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"680","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/680"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"680"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70871"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"559"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7270"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7627"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28461"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86589"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to the emergency department with a laceration to the dorsum of his left hand which occurred when a large sheet of glass fell onto his hand while at work.\u00a0He has been given adequate analgesia and his pain is under control. He states his last tetanus dose was \u0026gt;10 years ago, however he has never missed a vaccination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, when asked to extend his fingers the following view is seen (Image). He is still able to make a fist and maintains the ability to abduct his fingers. Capillary refill time is \u0026lt;2 seconds and he reports no altered sensation to light touch.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis vital signs are consistent with a blood pressure of 125/80 mmHg, a heart rate of 98/min and a respiratory rate of 18/min.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate course of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Immediately suture the wound using 2.0 vicryl","Organise a plastic surgery review with a view to surgical repair","Tetanus immunoglobulin","Perform a biers block and explore the wound for the location of the extensor tendon","Organise an outpatient MRI hand"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has suffered a complete laceration of the extensor tendon of the fourth digit and has thus lost the ability to extend the affected finger. Extensor tendon lacerations are relatively common injuries and, when not managed with the appropriate surgical interventions, may result in a lasting impairment of hand function. Extensor tendons in the hand are more injury prone than flexor tendons due to their superficial location and being adjacent to the bones. Therefore, the most appropriate step in management at this time is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eorganise a plastic surgery review\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Ewith a view to surgical repair \u003C/strong\u003Eand stabilisation of the wound bed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediately suturing the wound using 2.0 vicryl\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate given it does not address the underlying tendon injury and will not restore the functional impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe tetanus status of the patient does need to be reviewed and given his last tetanus vaccination dose was \u0026gt;10 years ago, he does require a tetanus vaccination dose. There is no need for \u003Cstrong\u003Etetanus immunoglobulin\u003C/strong\u003E with the above injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiers block and wound exploration\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate for the above patient. A Bier\u0027s block is a form of IV regional anaesthesia which involves injection of local anaesthetic into the venous system of an extremity which has previously been exsanguinated by gravity or compression. The local anaesthetic diffuses into the surrounding nerves. Local ischaemia, caused by the tourniquet, contributes to the analgesic effect. This process would be inappropriate for a medical intern to perform and location of the extensor tendon in the dorsum while in the ED is unlikely to be of assistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAn outpatient MRI hand \u003C/strong\u003Eis unlikely to provide any benefit and will only delay surgery and potentially worsen patient outcome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo years after the tendon repair: (Image)\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Extensor tendon laceration with loss of function requires surgical intervention"],"references":["Moore A, Marappa-Ganeshan R. Hand Extensor Tendon Lacerations. [Updated 2022 Aug 22]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK554431/","Table. Guide to tetanus prophylaxis in wound management. Australian Immunisation Handbook [Internet]. Australian Government. [Accessed 22 Feb 2025]. Available from: https://immunisationhandbook.health.gov.au/resources/tables/table-guide-to-tetanus-prophylaxis-in-wound-management","Jafarian A, Hassani V, Jesmi F, Ramezani K, Javaheri F, Shariatzadeh H. Efficacy of a Modified Bier\u0027s Block in Patients Undergoing Upper Limb Bone Surgery. Anesth Pain Med. 2015 Feb 28;5(1):e22007. doi: 10.5812/aapm.22007. PMID: 25789235; PMCID: PMC4350160. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4350160/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70871"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"680"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18264"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18265"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18264"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b40e56a6-bbad-4f2a-8873-be526c6642af.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b40e56a6-bbad-4f2a-8873-be526c6642af.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"18265","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18265"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a8877b79-caed-4f45-9b2d-9de86008b201.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a8877b79-caed-4f45-9b2d-9de86008b201.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70871","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70871"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-22T15:15:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-22T15:16:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"680"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86589"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"20","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/20"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4c","name":"Plastic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"